Note: ========================================
Note: GraphQL Translator Tests
Note: ========================================
Note: Comprehensive test suite for GraphQL translation system

Note: Test Coverage:
Note:   - Lexer tokenization tests
Note:   - Parser AST construction tests
Note:   - GraphQL→HIR translation tests
Note:   - HIR→GraphQL generation tests
Note:   - Round-trip translation tests
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/graphql/graphql_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/graphql/graphql_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/graphql/graphql_to_hir.runa" as ToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/graphql/hir_to_graphql.runa" as FromHIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ========================================
Note: Test Runner
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the GraphQL translator suite. Runs lexer,
four parser tests (query, mutation, fragments, directives), to-HIR,
from-HIR, and round-trip checks in dependency order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print banner, call each test_* proc serially. Failures reported
inline by assert_* helpers.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 8 tests print "[OK]" -> clean suite
- Any assert_* failure prints "FAILED:" line -> visible in CI
@End TestCases

Process called "run_all_graphql_tests":
    Note: Run complete GraphQL test suite

    proc print_string with "GraphQL Translator Test Suite"
    proc print_newline

    proc test_lexer_tokenization
    proc test_parser_query
    proc test_parser_mutation
    proc test_parser_fragments
    proc test_parser_directives
    proc test_graphql_to_hir
    proc test_hir_to_graphql
    proc test_round_trip

    proc print_newline
    proc print_string with "All GraphQL tests completed!"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Lexer Tokenization Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies GraphQL lexer across three input shapes: simple query
(exact-count check of 8 tokens including EOF), mutation with
variable declaration (count > 10), and fragment definition
(count > 5). The exact-count assertion on the query catches a
regression where EOF is omitted.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three tokenize+assert blocks:
1. "query { user { name } }" -> assert_equals 8 tokens.
2. "mutation CreateUser($name: String!) { createUser(name: $name) { id } }"
   -> assert_true count > 10.
3. "fragment UserFields on User { id name email }" -> assert_true
   count > 5.
Each block destroys its lexer before moving to the next.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "query { user { name } }" -> 8 tokens, passed
- Mutation with variables -> > 10 tokens, passed
- Fragment definition -> > 5 tokens, passed
- Lexer drops $name variable token -> "Mutation tokenization" fails
- Lexer doesn't recognize "fragment" keyword -> "Fragment tokenization" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_tokenization":
    Note: Test GraphQL lexer tokenization

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL lexer tokenization..."

    Note: Test basic query keyword
    Let query_source be proc create_string_literal with "query { user { name } }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with query_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Should have tokens: query, {, user, {, name, }, }, EOF
    proc assert_equals with token_count, 8, "Query tokenization count"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    Note: Test mutation with variables
    Let mutation_source be proc create_string_literal with "mutation CreateUser($name: String!) { createUser(name: $name) { id } }"
    Let lexer2 be proc create_lexer from Lexer with mutation_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer2

    Let tokens2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer2, 40
    Let token_count2 be proc size from List with tokens2

    Note: Should tokenize mutation, variables, arguments, etc.
    Let _mut_ok be token_count2 is greater than 10
    proc assert_true with _mut_ok, "Mutation tokenization"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer2

    Note: Test fragment spread
    Let fragment_source be proc create_string_literal with "fragment UserFields on User { id name email }"
    Let lexer3 be proc create_lexer from Lexer with fragment_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer3

    Let tokens3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer3, 40
    Let token_count3 be proc size from List with tokens3

    Note: Should have fragment keyword, name, on, type, fields
    Let _frag_ok be token_count3 is greater than 5
    proc assert_true with _frag_ok, "Fragment tokenization"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer3

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Lexer tokenization tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Query Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the GraphQL parser builds the canonical AST shape for a
named query and an argumented query. Checks AST root type tag (1 =
GRAPHQL_DOCUMENT), child count exactly 1 (one top-level operation),
and the operation's type tag (2 = GRAPHQL_OPERATION). The
argumented-query variant verifies the same shape survives variable
declarations and field arguments.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two parse+assert blocks:
1. "query GetUser { user { id name } }" -> assert root tag == 1,
   child count == 1, first child operation tag == 2.
2. "query GetUserById($id: ID!) { user(id: $id) { name } }" ->
   assert child count == 1.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "query GetUser { ... }" -> root 1, children=1, first op tag 2, passed
- Parser builds wrong root tag -> "AST root is GRAPHQL_DOCUMENT" fails
- Parser drops the operation -> "Document has one operation" fails
- "query GetUserById($id: ID!) { user(id: $id) { name } }" -> child count 1
- Argument parser fails -> child count != 1
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_query":
    Note: Test GraphQL query parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL query parsing..."

    Note: Test simple query
    Let query_source be proc create_string_literal with "query GetUser { user { id name } }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with query_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    Note: Check AST structure
    Let ast_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 0
    proc assert_equals with ast_type, 1, "AST root is GRAPHQL_DOCUMENT"

    Note: Check operation
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    proc assert_equals with child_count, 1, "Document has one operation"

    Let operation be proc get from List with children, 0
    Let operation_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with operation, 0
    proc assert_equals with operation_type, 2, "First child is GRAPHQL_OPERATION"

    proc destroy_graphql_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    Note: Test query with arguments
    Let query_args_source be proc create_string_literal with "query GetUserById($id: ID!) { user(id: $id) { name } }"
    Let lexer2 be proc create_lexer from Lexer with query_args_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer2

    Let parser2 be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer2
    Let ast2 be proc parse from Parser with parser2

    Let children2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast2, 32
    Let child_count2 be proc size from List with children2
    proc assert_equals with child_count2, 1, "Query with args has one operation"

    proc destroy_graphql_node from Parser with ast2
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser2
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer2

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Query parsing tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Mutation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser distinguishes mutation operations from queries.
The operation's type-code field (offset 24) carries the
enum tag for operation kind; 11 = mutation. Catches a regression
where the parser tags a mutation as a query.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize+parse `mutation CreateUser { createUser(name: "Alice") { id } }`.
Walk to the first operation child, read offset 24, assert == 11.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- mutation with string-literal argument -> operation_type_code == 11, passed
- Parser tags as query -> operation_type_code != 11 -> "Operation type is mutation (11)" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_mutation":
    Note: Test GraphQL mutation parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL mutation parsing..."

    Note: Test mutation
    Let mutation_source be proc create_string_literal with "mutation CreateUser { createUser(name: \"Alice\") { id } }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with mutation_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    Note: Check operation type
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let operation be proc get from List with children, 0
    Let operation_type_code be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with operation, 24
    proc assert_equals with operation_type_code, 11, "Operation type is mutation (11)"

    proc destroy_graphql_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Mutation parsing tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Fragment Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles both fragment forms: fragment definition
("fragment UserFields on User { ... }") and fragment spread
("...UserFields" inside a selection set). The definition is tagged
GRAPHQL_FRAGMENT_DEF (5); the spread is parsed inside a regular
query so the assertion is only that the document parses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two parse+assert blocks:
1. Fragment definition -> first child tag == 5 (GRAPHQL_FRAGMENT_DEF).
2. Query with spread "...UserFields" -> root tag == 1 (parses successfully).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "fragment UserFields on User { id name email }" -> tag 5, passed
- "query { user { ...UserFields } }" -> root 1, passed
- Parser fails on "on" keyword -> "Fragment is GRAPHQL_FRAGMENT_DEF (5)" fails
- Parser fails on "..." spread -> "Fragment spread query parsed" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_fragments":
    Note: Test GraphQL fragment parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL fragment parsing..."

    Note: Test fragment definition
    Let fragment_source be proc create_string_literal with "fragment UserFields on User { id name email }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with fragment_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    Note: Check fragment
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let fragment be proc get from List with children, 0
    Let fragment_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with fragment, 0
    proc assert_equals with fragment_type, 5, "Fragment is GRAPHQL_FRAGMENT_DEF (5)"

    proc destroy_graphql_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    Note: Test fragment spread usage
    Let spread_source be proc create_string_literal with "query { user { ...UserFields } }"
    Let lexer2 be proc create_lexer from Lexer with spread_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer2

    Let parser2 be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer2
    Let ast2 be proc parse from Parser with parser2

    Note: Should parse successfully
    Let ast2_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast2, 0
    proc assert_equals with ast2_type, 1, "Fragment spread query parsed"

    proc destroy_graphql_node from Parser with ast2
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser2
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer2

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Fragment parsing tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Directive Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles GraphQL field directives (@skip, @include
with arguments). Multiple directives on different fields in the same
selection set exercises the directive list parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize+parse a query with @skip(if: true) and @include(if: false)
on two fields. Assert root AST tag == 1 (parses successfully).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Query with two @-directives -> root 1, passed
- Parser fails on @ token -> "Directive query parsed" fails
- Parser fails on directive argument -> ast == 0 -> fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_directives":
    Note: Test GraphQL directive parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL directive parsing..."

    Note: Test directives on fields
    Let directive_source be proc create_string_literal with "query { user { name @skip(if: true) email @include(if: false) } }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with directive_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    Note: Should parse successfully
    Let ast_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 0
    proc assert_equals with ast_type, 1, "Directive query parsed"

    proc destroy_graphql_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Directive parsing tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: GraphQL to HIR Translation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
End-to-end GraphQL source-to-HIR check. HIR contract is a dict with
"type" = "document" and a "definitions" list containing exactly
one entry for the single top-level operation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Lex+parse "query { user { name } }".
2. translate_graphql_to_hir(ast) -> hir.
3. Dict.get(hir, "type"); assert string equals "document".
4. Dict.get(hir, "definitions"); assert size == 1.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "query { user { name } }" -> HIR with type "document" and one definition, passed
- HIR.type != "document" -> "HIR type is document" fails
- HIR.definitions has zero or multiple entries -> "HIR has one definition" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_graphql_to_hir":
    Note: Test GraphQL AST to HIR translation

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL→HIR translation..."

    Note: Test simple query translation
    Let query_source be proc create_string_literal with "query { user { name } }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with query_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    Note: Translate to HIR
    Let hir be proc translate_graphql_to_hir from ToHIR with ast

    Note: Check HIR structure
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc get from Dict with hir, type_key
    Let type_str be proc to_cstring from StringCore with type_value

    proc assert_string_equals with type_str, "document", "HIR type is document"

    Note: Check definitions
    Let definitions_key be proc create_string_literal with "definitions"
    Let definitions be proc get from Dict with hir, definitions_key
    Let def_count be proc size from List with definitions
    proc assert_equals with def_count, 1, "HIR has one definition"

    proc destroy_graphql_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    proc print_string with "  ✓ GraphQL→HIR translation tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: HIR to GraphQL Generation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Reverse direction: construct a hand-built HIR for "query { user }"
and assert the emitter produces output containing both "query" and
"user" keywords. Isolates the emitter from frontend bugs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build HIR dict with type="document", definitions=[operation].
2. operation has type="operation", operation_type="query",
   selections=[field].
3. field has type="field", name="user".
4. generate_graphql_from_hir(hir) -> graphql_output.
5. string_contains(graphql_output, "query") == 1 AND ditto "user".
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Hand-built HIR -> output contains "query" and "user", passed
- Emitter drops "query" keyword -> "Generated GraphQL contains query" fails
- Emitter drops field name -> "Generated GraphQL contains user" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_hir_to_graphql":
    Note: Test HIR to GraphQL generation

    proc print_string with "Testing HIR→GraphQL generation..."

    Note: Create test HIR manually
    Let hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set document type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "document"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Create operation
    Let operation be proc create from Dict
    Let op_type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let op_type_value be proc create_string_literal with "operation"
    proc set from Dict with operation, op_type_key, op_type_value

    Let op_operation_type_key be proc create_string_literal with "operation_type"
    Let op_operation_type_value be proc create_string_literal with "query"
    proc set from Dict with operation, op_operation_type_key, op_operation_type_value

    Note: Create field
    Let field be proc create from Dict
    Let field_type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let field_type_value be proc create_string_literal with "field"
    proc set from Dict with field, field_type_key, field_type_value

    Let field_name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
    Let field_name_value be proc create_string_literal with "user"
    proc set from Dict with field, field_name_key, field_name_value

    Note: Create selections list with field
    Let selections be proc create from List
    proc push from List with selections, field

    Let selections_key be proc create_string_literal with "selections"
    proc set from Dict with operation, selections_key, selections

    Note: Add operation to definitions
    Let definitions be proc create from List
    proc push from List with definitions, operation

    Let definitions_key be proc create_string_literal with "definitions"
    proc set from Dict with hir, definitions_key, definitions

    Note: Generate GraphQL
    Let graphql_output be proc generate_graphql_from_hir from FromHIR with hir

    Note: Check output contains "query"
    Let contains_query be proc string_contains with graphql_output, "query"
    proc assert_equals with contains_query, 1, "Generated GraphQL contains query"

    Let contains_user be proc string_contains with graphql_output, "user"
    proc assert_equals with contains_user, 1, "Generated GraphQL contains user"

    proc print_string with "  ✓ HIR→GraphQL generation tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Round-Trip Translation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Full pipeline check: GraphQL source -> tokens -> AST -> HIR ->
GraphQL text. Three contains-checks ("query", "user", "id")
verify the three salient tokens survive both translation directions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Tokenize+parse "query GetUser { user { id name email } }".
2. translate_graphql_to_hir -> hir; generate_graphql_from_hir ->
   graphql_output.
3. string_contains assertions for "query", "user", "id".
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "query GetUser { user { id name email } }" -> output contains
  query+user+id, passed
- Emitter drops operation keyword -> "Round-trip contains query" fails
- Emitter drops field -> "Round-trip contains user" or "Round-trip contains id" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_round_trip":
    Note: Test GraphQL → HIR → GraphQL round-trip

    proc print_string with "Testing round-trip translation..."

    Note: Test simple query round-trip
    Let query_source be proc create_string_literal with "query GetUser { user { id name email } }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with query_source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    Note: GraphQL → HIR
    Let hir be proc translate_graphql_to_hir from ToHIR with ast

    Note: HIR → GraphQL
    Let graphql_output be proc generate_graphql_from_hir from FromHIR with hir

    Note: Check semantic equivalence (contains key elements)
    Let contains_query be proc string_contains with graphql_output, "query"
    proc assert_equals with contains_query, 1, "Round-trip contains query"

    Let contains_user be proc string_contains with graphql_output, "user"
    proc assert_equals with contains_user, 1, "Round-trip contains user"

    Let contains_id be proc string_contains with graphql_output, "id"
    proc assert_equals with contains_id, 1, "Round-trip contains id"

    Let contains_name be proc string_contains with graphql_output, "name"
    proc assert_equals with contains_name, 1, "Round-trip contains name"

    proc destroy_graphql_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    proc print_string with "  ✓ Round-trip translation tests passed"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Helper Functions
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Equality assertion. Failure prints just the message; no operand
echo because this suite's callers tend to put the expected value
into the message string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If actual != expected, print "FAILED: <message>" + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_equals" takes actual as Integer, expected as Integer, message as String:
    Note: Assert two integers are equal

    If actual is not equal to expected:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string from message
        proc print_string with " (expected: "
        proc print_integer from expected
        proc print_string with ", actual: "
        proc print_integer from actual
        proc print_string with ")"
        proc print_newline
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean assertion. Failure prints just the message.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If condition != 1, print "FAILED: <message>" + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_true" takes condition as Integer, message as String:
    Note: Assert condition is true

    If condition is not equal to 1:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string from message
        proc print_newline
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
String equality assertion. Failure prints both strings so a tester
sees exactly where the mismatch is.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Call string_equals(actual, expected). If 0, print "FAILED: <message>
(expected '<expected>', got '<actual>')" + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_string_equals" takes actual as String, expected as String, message as String:
    Note: Assert two strings are equal

    Let are_equal be proc string_equals with actual, expected

    If are_equal is not equal to 1:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string from message
        proc print_string with " (expected: "
        proc print_string from expected
        proc print_string with ", actual: "
        proc print_string from actual
        proc print_string with ")"
        proc print_newline
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Byte-by-byte C-string equality comparator. Operates on null-
terminated strings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk index i upward, read both bytes via memory_get_byte. Mismatch
-> 0. Both null -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_equals" takes str1 as String, str2 as String returns Integer:
    Note: Compare two null-terminated C strings for equality

    Let i be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str1, i
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str2, i

        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If

        If c1 is equal to 0:
            Return 1  Note: Both strings ended at same point
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Naive substring search used by emitter and round-trip tests to
verify GraphQL keywords survive translation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Empty needle -> 1. needle > haystack -> 0. Slide window over
haystack; if all needle bytes match at any position -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_contains" takes haystack as String, needle as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check if haystack contains needle substring

    Let haystack_len be proc string_length from StringCore with haystack
    Let needle_len be proc string_length from StringCore with needle

    If needle_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: Empty string is always contained
    End If

    If needle_len is greater than haystack_len:
        Return 0  Note: Needle can't be contained if longer than haystack
    End If

    Let i be 0
    Let max_i be haystack_len minus needle_len

    While i is less than or equal to max_i:
        Let matches be 1
        Let j be 0

        While j is less than needle_len:
            Let h_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with haystack, i plus j
            Let n_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with needle, j

            If h_char is not equal to n_char:
                Set matches to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper around StringCore.create_string_from_literal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forward to StringCore.create_string_from_literal(value).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Note: Create string from string literal

    Return proc create_string_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process

Note: print_string, print_newline, and print_integer are runtime-provided
Note: (codegen emits them as syscall-write wrappers); test code calls them directly.
